{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17526714","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17526714"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T15:25:00+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T15:25:00+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14151"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14151","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14151"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.73,0.1,0.11,0.01,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6834"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55832"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6834","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6834"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14151"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41378"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"2"},{"type":"tags","id":"12"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1481"},{"type":"tags","id":"4069"},{"type":"tags","id":"4953"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"9641"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"15450"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43496"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55832","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55832"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 22-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic for a routine check-up. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. On examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 72/min, blood pressure 150/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 14/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.6\u00b0C. He is notably tall at 198 cm, with long, slender limbs and fingers. His arm span exceeds his height by 8 cm. He has mild scoliosis and a high-arched palate. Cardiovascular examination reveals a murmur.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely murmur associated with this patient\u0027s condition?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Aortic regurgitation","Aortic stenosis","Mitral stenosis","Pulmonary stenosis","Tricuspid regurgitation"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with several clinical features suggestive of Marfan syndrome, including tall stature, long limbs, arachnodactyly (long, slender fingers), arm span exceeding height, scoliosis, and high-arched palate. Marfan syndrome is an autosomal dominant connective tissue disorder caused by mutations in the fibrillin-1 gene.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn Marfan syndrome, the most common cardiovascular manifestation is progressive dilatation of the aortic root, which can lead to \u003Cstrong\u003Eaortic regurgitation\u003C/strong\u003E. The murmur of aortic regurgitation is typically a high-pitched, blowing, diastolic murmur heard best at the left lower sternal edge. The wide pulse pressure (150/60 mmHg) in this patient also supports the presence of aortic regurgitation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAortic stenosis\u003C/strong\u003E is not typically associated with Marfan syndrome. The murmur of aortic stenosis is a harsh, systolic ejection murmur heard best at the right upper sternal border and often radiates to the carotids. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMitral stenosis\u003C/strong\u003E is not a common feature of Marfan syndrome. Its murmur is a low-pitched, rumbling diastolic murmur heard best at the apex with the patient in the left lateral decubitus position. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPulmonary stenosis\u003C/strong\u003E is not typically associated with Marfan syndrome. Its murmur is a systolic ejection murmur heard best at the left upper sternal border. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETricuspid regurgitation\u003C/strong\u003E can occur in Marfan syndrome but is less common than aortic regurgitation. Its murmur is a high-pitched, blowing, holosystolic murmur heard best at the left lower sternal border, which increases with inspiration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn addition to the cardiovascular features, patients with Marfan syndrome may have ocular manifestations (lens dislocation, myopia), skeletal abnormalities (pectus excavatum or carinatum), and other systemic features. Echocardiography is crucial in these patients to assess aortic root diameter and valvular function. Regular follow-up and potentially prophylactic aortic root surgery may be necessary to prevent life-threatening aortic dissection.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Marfan syndrome is associated with aortic root dilatation, which can lead to aortic regurgitation.","Key features of Marfan syndrome include tall stature, long limbs, arachnodactyly, and lens dislocation.","Echocardiography is an important investigation in patients with suspected Marfan syndrome to assess for aortic root dilatation and valvular abnormalities."],"references":["Isekame Y, Gati S, Aragon-Martin JA, Bastiaenen R, Kondapally Seshasai SR, Child A. Cardiovascular Management of Adults with Marfan Syndrome. European Cardiology Review. 2016;11(2):102. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/30310455/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41378"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14151"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41378","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/41378"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-18T11:48:53+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-18T11:49:27+10:30"},"relationships"